Create one persistent Node.js Jazz context once in a server-only module and reuse it across requests.

```ts
// backend/jazz.ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import { permissions } from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH || "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL, // only if needed for sync topology
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});

export async function shutdown() {
  await jazz.shutdown();
}
```

Important constraints:
- Install `jazz-napi` directly for Node runtimes.
- Prefer `persistent` driver in durable Node services; `memory` requires `serverUrl` because it is not durable by itself.
- `BACKEND_SECRET` is required for backend/scoped APIs (`asBackend`, `forRequest`, `withAttribution*`) on a server-connected setup; keep it server-only.
- Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` / `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` in server-only env vars (never public env prefixes).
- Do not recreate context per request. Register process exit handlers (`SIGINT`, `SIGTERM`) to call `jazz.shutdown()`.
- In framework/serverless dev environments, ensure singleton reuse across reloads rather than hot-spawning runtimes.
- For endpoints that promise durable visibility, await explicit write tier confirmation (`.wait({ tier: "edge" })` when appropriate).

Pass a **query factory/accessor**, not a frozen query object, whenever inputs are reactive.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

let selectedProjectId = $state<string | null>(null);
const todosSub = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc")
);

// read: todosSub.current / todosSub.loading / todosSub.error
```

Solid:
```tsx
import { useAll, useDb } from "jazz-tools/solid";

const doneFilter = createSignal(false);
const todos = () => useAll(() =>
  app.todos.where({ done: doneFilter() }).orderBy("title", "asc")
);
```

(If query inputs are static, passing a built query is fine; for dynamic inputs, always use the accessor form.)

Use `db.batch(...)` for grouped optimistic UI writes that should surface immediately locally and need single local-settlement semantics.

Use `db.transaction(...)` when both writes must be accepted by authority together and become visible atomically at global durability.

```ts
// optimistic UI grouping
db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, idA, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, idB, { done: true });
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });

// must wait for authority + global atomicity
await (await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, idA, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, idB, { done: true });
})).wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Upload must not return success until edge has all chunks:
```ts
const file = await db.createFileFromBlob(app, blob, { tier: "edge" });
const upload = await db.insert(app.uploads, {
  owner_id: session.user_id,
  label: "Profile photo",
  fileId: file.id,
}).wait({ tier: "edge" });
```
For binary stream use `createFileFromStream(..., { tier: "edge" })`.
Handle download incomplete states explicitly:
```ts
try {
  const blob = await db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "local" });
} catch (err) {
  if (err.name === "IncompleteFileDataError") {
    // local has missing/corrupt chunks; retry against stronger tier
    return db.loadFileAsBlob(app, upload.fileId, { tier: "edge" });
  }
  if (err.name === "FileNotFoundError") throw err;
}
```
`IncompleteFileDataError` means missing chunk or mismatch; retrying with a stronger tier is the recovery path for eventual consistency gaps.

Delete in dependency order while inherited delete access is still valid:
```ts
const upload = await db.one(app.uploads.where({ id: uploadId }), { tier: "edge" });
if (!upload) return;

const file = upload.fileId
  ? await db.one(app.files.where({ id: upload.fileId }), { tier: "edge" })
  : null;

if (file) {
  for (const partId of file.partIds) {
    db.delete(app.file_parts, partId);
  }
  db.delete(app.files, file.id);
}

db.delete(app.uploads, upload.id);
```
Do **not** delete `uploads` first; inherited file/part delete permissions are often derived from the parent relationship and can disappear before cleanup. Treat files/parts as write-once and delete old references/rows explicitly.

Use a dedicated typed projection layer around `JazzClient` boundary; do not invent Rust handles for tables.

1) Keep schema/query order explicit and immutable:
```rust
let schema = SchemaBuilder::new()
  .table(TableSchema::builder("todos").column("title", ColumnType::Text).column("done", ColumnType::Boolean).nullable_column("description", ColumnType::Text).build())
  .build();
```

2) Define domain rows and one strict decoder per projection:
```rust
struct TodoRow { id: ObjectId, title: String, done: bool, description: Option<String> }
fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
  if values.len()!=3 { return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch); }
  let title = values[0].as_string()?.ok_or(AppError::SchemaMismatch)?;
  let done = values[1].as_bool().ok_or(AppError::SchemaMismatch)?;
  let description = match &values[2] { Value::Null => None, Value::Text(s)=>Some(s.clone()), _=>return Err(AppError::SchemaMismatch)};
  Ok(TodoRow{id,title,done,description})
}
```

3) Query -> decode immediately:
```rust
let rows: Vec<(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)> = client.query(QueryBuilder::table("todos").select(["title","done","description"]).build())?;
let todos = rows.into_iter().map(|(id,v)| decode_todo(id,v)).collect::<Result<Vec<_>,_>>()?;
```

4) For writes, use `row_input!`, and keep one `BatchId`/durability wait path for all mutating flows.

Use a cross-client sync topology (`startLocalJazzServer` + two `createDb` clients) and assert by stable IDs, not array order.

```ts
import { createDb } from "jazz-tools";
import { startLocalJazzServer, vi, expect } from "vitest";

const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
const alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
const bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });

it("syncs multiple rows with deterministic assertions", async () => {
  const created = await Promise.all([
    alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Beta" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alpha" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
    alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Gamma" }).wait({ tier: "edge" }),
  ]);

  const expected = created
    .map((r) => ({ id: r.id, title: r.title }))
    .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

  await vi.waitFor(async () => {
    const remoteRows = await Promise.all(
      created.map((r) => bob.one(app.todos.where({ id: r.id }), { tier: "edge" })),
    );

    const actual = remoteRows
      .filter(Boolean)
      .map((r) => ({ id: r.id, title: r.title }))
      .sort((a, b) => a.id.localeCompare(b.id));

    expect(actual).toEqual(expected);
  });
});
```

Key point: no explicit row-order assertion (`toEqual` on full unsorted arrays) and no fixed sleeps; rely on `wait({tier: "edge"})` + `waitFor`.

Use policy testing (`createPolicyTestApp`) and assert denied read + denied write as separate operations.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { describe, beforeEach, afterEach, expect, it } from "vitest";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob from reading and writing Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({ user_id: "alice", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });
  const bob = testApp.as({ user_id: "bob", claims: {}, authMode: "local-first" });

  const row = alice.insert(app.notes, { title: "private" }).value;

  bob.expectDenied((db) => db.update(app.notes, row.id, { title: "hacked" }));
  bob.expectDenied((db) => db.delete(app.notes, row.id));

  await expect(bob.all(app.notes.where({ id: row.id }))).resolves.toEqual([]);
  await alice.expectAllowed((db) => db.one(app.notes.where({ id: row.id })));
});
```

If your policy scopes by creator/owner, verify the seed session writes that policy preconditions (e.g., owner field) before asserting these behaviors.
